<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900620-0143</DOCNO><DOCID>900620-0143.</DOCID><HL>   Bell Atlantic to Buy   Simborg, Hospital   Data Systems Firm   ----   By Pamela J. Podger   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>06/20/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   BEL WNEWS</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   PHILADELPHIA -- Bell Atlantic Corp. said it signed anagreement to acquire Simborg Systems Corp. in an all-stocktransaction but didn't disclose the terms.   Closely held Simborg, based in Greenbrae, Calif., developshospital information management systems and is a pioneer inopen architecture systems for the health care industry.</LP><TEXT>   Bell Atlantic is a telecommunications company.   Bell Atlantic said the purchase -- which would involve itsfirst subsidiary in the hospital information industry -- willbe closed within 60 days and the venture will be renamed BellAtlantic Healthcare Systems, providing total patient caresolutions for hospitals and other health care facilities inthe U.S.and Canada.   Donald W. Simborg, who founded the company in 1984, willbecome president of Bell Atlantic Healthcare Systems. All ofSimborg Systems' 40 employees are expected to join the newcompany, Bell Atlantic said.   Simborg System's STAT LAN hospital network product,currently used in 25 U.S. hospitals, will complement networkand business systems offered by Bell Atlantic units.   &quot;STAT LAN is a backbone to a network to which a customercan plug in applications,&quot; a Bell Atlantic spokeswoman said.   &quot;Healthcare is a major thrust for Bell Atlantic,&quot; saidJeffrey S. McDermott, president of Bell Atlantic Software andSystems Solutions division, which will oversee theacquisition.   The STAT LAN health care information network uses thelatest local area network and microcomputer technology,allowing different hospital departments to run independentsystems and to share information over the network.   The company said Bell Atlantic Healthcare Systems willmarket sales of STAT LAN and will continue joint marketingaccords with distributors such as Andersen Consulting andAmeritech Corp., both based in Chicago.   Douglas Ryckman, managing partner of Andersen Consulting,said hospital systems must evolve to include openarchitecture and networking.   Industry consultant Sheldon Dorenfest said the deeppockets of Bell Atlantic will give Simborg Systems the&quot;resources and staying power to further enhance STAT LAN andbecome a major player in health care information systems.&quot;   Clayton Brown, an analyst for A.G. Edwards in New York,said the venture is another way for Bell Atlantic todiversify. &quot;The deal is different from Bell Atlantic'scellular phone and yellow pages mainstays,&quot; he said.   Bell Atlantic shares closed yesterday at $49.75, off 25cents, in New York Stock Exchange composite trading.</TEXT></DOC>